text:
A general view northwestward from the Harriet Hubbard Ayer Building at No. 321 E. 34th Street, north side, between First and Second Avenue, showing skyscrapers of the 42nd Street - Midtown area of Manhattan. From left to right (across the three views) they are: the 10 East 40th Street Building; the Lefcourt - Colonial Building (under construction); the Lincoln Building; the Chanin Building; and the Chrysler Building, (under construction). In the foreground is the Second Avenue "El" with a corner of St. Gabriels Park on the easterly side and tenements to the west.

September 10, 1929.
Views 1,2 and 3

P.L. Sperr

text:
321 East 34th Street (Harriet Hubbard Ayer Building) north side, between First and Second Avenues, showing a (general view westward) and viewing to the north, across Second Avenue and its "El" line.

On this side of same, appears, the westerly portion of St. Gabriel's Park (35th-36th Street's) and the future plaza of the Midtown-Queens Tunnel (36th-37th Street's).

At the right background beyond this section of Murray Hill, are the skyscrapers forming the 42nd Street outline. The bases of these in View 3 are, from left to right respectively, the Lincoln, the Chanin, the Chrysler and the News Buildings.

October 13, 1939
Views 1, 2, 3

P. L. Sperr

321 East 34th Street (Harriet Hubbard Ayer Building) north side, between First and Second Avenues, showing a (general view northeastward).

The photographers direction is towards the East River and he is viewing across the easterly half of St. Gabriel's Park, to the Manhattan entrance and future plaza of the Midtown-Queens Tunnel at First Avenue and East 37th Street.

View No. 3 is slightly east and shows prominently the New York Steam Company plant at 35th Street.

text:
321 East 34th Street (Harriet Hubbard Ayer Building) north side, between First and Second Avenues, showing a (general view north and northeastward across the future plaza entrance of the Midtown-Queens Tunnel. This will included the entire 36th-37th Street block between the aforementioned Avenues. The low buildings framing the distant edge are on the north side of East 37th Street. To the right is First Avenue and it's New York Edison Company power plant. Beyond are the distinctive apartment structures comprising Tudor City at 42nd Street.

October 13, 1939
Views 1, 2, 3

P. L. Sperr

text:
321 East 34th Street (Harriet Hubbard Ayer Building) north side, between First and Second Avenues, showing a (general view northward) across St. Gabriel's Park and the future entrance to the Midtown-Queens Tunnel.

Both of these are between the aforementioned Avenues, the former occupying the 35th-36th block and the latter, the next block north. Buildings seen in the background framing the clearance, are on the north side of 37th Street. Tudor City is at 42nd St. The Hotel Woodstock of same is in the center.

October 13, 1939
Views 1, 2, 3
